# Response-length commands

When the user's message contains one of the slash commands below (anywhere in the message, case-insensitive), constrain that turn's response to the matching length budget. Commands apply to **that single turn only** — the next message returns to default behavior unless re-issued.

If multiple commands appear, the **shortest** wins. If a command would force me to omit information that is genuinely needed for correctness or safety, I keep the answer correct and note the conflict in one brief sentence.

If the user is asking *about* a command rather than invoking it ("what does /tldr do?"), answer the question normally — don't apply the budget.

## Commands

| Command | Length budget | Allowed formatting |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `/oneliner` | 1 sentence, ≤30 words | Plain prose only — no code, no lists, no headers |
| `/tldr` | ≤3 sentences, ≤75 words | Plain prose only — no code, no lists, no headers |
| `/short` | 1 paragraph, ≤120 words | Inline code OK; no fenced blocks, no headers, no lists |
| `/medium` | 2–3 paragraphs, ≤300 words | Inline code + short lists; one fenced code block max if essential |
| `/long` | No hard word cap, but stay focused on what was asked | Full markdown — headers, lists, multiple code blocks |
| `/code` | Code-only response, prose ≤2 sentences per block | One or more code blocks or code references |
| `/normal` | Default behavior — no length constraint | Whatever the situation calls for |

## Behavior

- The command token controls **how** I answer, not **what** I answer. Strip it from the user's intent and answer the underlying question.
- Stay inside the budget even if I have more to say. Pick the highest-signal pieces and drop the rest.
- For `/oneliner` and `/tldr`, never use bullet points, headers, or code blocks — even for multi-part answers.
- For `/code`, prefer code references (with file path and line numbers) over markdown code blocks when the code already exists in the codebase.
- Never apologize for brevity caused by these commands. The user asked for it.

## Example

User: `/tldr how does the batch fact-checker work?`

Good (3 sentences, no headers, no lists): "The endpoint pulls articles from WordPress sorted by `_article_meeting_date`, then for each one looks up the transcript in SQLite by `youtube_id` and runs an xAI fact-check against article body and bullet points. Each article produces up to two report entries (one per scope). Failures are returned per-item rather than aborting the batch."

Bad (uses headers and bullets despite `/tldr`): "## Overview\n- Pulls articles from WordPress\n- Looks up transcript in SQLite..."
